english:
  title: Record of the Hermitage of Sufficiency
  author: Im Chun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    All sublime and extraordinary vistas—those rare jewels of landscape—are wrought by heaven and treasured by earth. Yet they dwell invariably in the deep recesses of mountains or remote coastal reaches, hidden in forsaken margins. There, colliding waves and rushing torrents crush down, cliffs crumble and boulders tumble. Dragons and serpents, vipers and beasts prowl those precincts. Thus, to glimpse such wonders, one must pack provisions, journey night and day without rest, endure the turning seasons—only then does one arrive. How rare it is, how exceedingly rare, that a man seated in his own chamber, without venturing beyond the city walls, without moving earth or laying stone to artificially heighten the ground, should yet obtain such transcendent views. Perhaps once in a thousand years does fortune grant such a thing.

    West of the Wangnyun Temple stands a hermitage, wherein dwelt a venerable master named Cheon. The hermitage was fashioned from curved rafters and bent pillars, fashioned to their natural form—neither lacquered nor whitewashed—achieving that perfect balance between refinement and rusticity. Ascending to its heights, the vista opens vast and luminous; one can discern the very back of soaring birds. Layered peaks encircle like a girdle, overgrown paths wind in misty dimness—all the wanderers who come and go remain visible from a single chair and mat. Truly, this is a jewel among the realm's finest places.

    The master arrived from the southern lands and dwelt here two years. Once he sighed deeply and said: "I am born into the age of decline, when the teaching weakens and the sacred way fades. Bearing the Buddha's treasury on my back, I should bid farewell to the world forever and retreat to hidden valleys to spend my remaining years." Yet when he resolved to wander among celebrated mountains and distant peaks, those scholarly officials who had long befriended him so loved his company that they could not bear his departure. Thus his travels were forestalled. Yet whether he stayed or went, his mind remained unbound—like an idle cloud drifting without intent, going and staying equally free.

    Always he kept to the hermitage, eyes closed in quiet meditation. Save for morning and evening chanting, he had no worldly concerns. On fair and luminous days, he would lead guests into the forest to gather fruit and vegetables whose fragrance and flavor pleased the palate. The table held fine fare, the cup held excellent wine. Cool breezes swept the courtyard; the bright moon attended his seat. He would grind spring tea, its fragrant essence sweet as spring water; he would play the silk strings, and wild birds would peer from their nests. Some guests grew merry with wine and sang with fervor; others walked in contemplation, their eyes transcending all things, wandering freely at ease—each finding satisfaction in their own way, though their pleasures differed.

    Before this, the hermitage had never been recorded in writing. During my visit, the master graciously asked me to compose an account and give the place a name. Though I demurred, he insisted, so I named it the Hermitage of Sufficiency. Yet the master seemed to find the name wanting, and said: "Those grand halls with painted eaves and carved railings, with jeweled ceilings and silken screens stretching cloudlike toward the sun, their thousand gates opened wide and walls extending for miles—such are the Chang Yang and Wu Zuo palaces, monuments to architectural grandeur. Those tossing seas, angry waves surging endlessly, with merchant vessels and trading ships bearing their sails through misty vapors—such are Dongting and Penglihu lakes, epitomes of majestic landscape. Yet you deem this humble hermitage sufficient? Is this not too modest?"

    I replied: "Things are infinite, but the body finite. Must one possess all the world's treasures to call oneself content? Those who lick others' wounds for gain, who steal in the marketplace—such people labor unto death yet never know satisfaction. But if one empties the heart, accepts one's station, and finds peace in fate itself, then even one branch suffices for rest, one handful for sustenance—where then cannot one find sufficiency? This hermitage is cramped and confined, barely sheltering from wind and rain. Yet to dwell here in ease, finding joy within these narrow bounds—does this not surpass the need for soaring pavilions and connected chambers gleaming with splendor? The streamlet below, its murmuring voice so pleasant to the ear, suffices without the thundering grandeur of great rivers and lakes, whose roar shakes the very earth. The peaks encircling before us, their mist-wreathed forms lovely to behold, suffice without the towering majesty of sacred mountains, where light and shadow shift as thunder and clouds gather. Thus is sufficiency defined.

    Yet know this: form follows substance, and things arise from the self. The master seeks to transcend all things and form, to stand alone in emptiness. When the self is not possessed, what then of this hermitage?"
